𝗣𝗲𝗿𝗳𝗼𝗿𝗺𝗮𝗻𝗰𝗲 𝗥𝗲𝘃𝗶𝗲𝘄𝘀 𝗡𝗲𝗲𝗱 𝗮 𝗥𝗲𝘀𝗲𝘁
Somewhere along the way, annual performance reviews drifted from their original purpose.
Under the COSO ERM framework, competence is a risk. The question is simple: Is the person you hired competent to do the job?

That’s it. A straightforward risk assessment that has become arduous, superfluous, and reactive. Most organizations don’t use performance reviews to assess or monitor risk. They use them to satisfy a process. We can do better.

𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝘁𝘄𝗼 𝗾𝘂𝗲𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻𝘀 𝗮 𝗿𝗲𝘃𝗶𝗲𝘄 𝘀𝗵𝗼𝘂𝗹𝗱 𝗮𝗻𝘀𝘄𝗲𝗿
A performance review should be a simple, risk‑aligned conversation:
• Did we check the box on our three priorities from last year?
• What three do we want for this year?

For example: Last year’s priority was implementing Power BI company‑wide. From that came several sub‑goals: learn Power BI, build models, deploy dashboards.

Clear objectives. Clear risks. Clear mitigation.

𝗪𝗲𝗲𝗸𝗹𝘆 𝗼𝗻𝗲‑𝗼𝗻‑𝗼𝗻𝗲𝘀 𝗲𝗹𝗶𝗺𝗶𝗻𝗮𝘁𝗲 𝟵𝟱% 𝗼𝗳 𝗿𝗲𝘃𝗶𝗲𝘄 𝗱𝗿𝗮𝗺𝗮
If you’re meeting weekly and asking: What did we accomplish or learn? What do we need to do next? Then the annual review becomes a summary, not a surprise.

If an issue shows up in an annual review that wasn’t addressed earlier, that’s not an employee issue — that’s a management issue.

No drama. No surprises. No negativity. Just continuous risk monitoring.

𝗛𝗥 𝘀𝗵𝗼𝘂𝗹𝗱 𝗯𝗲 𝗮𝗻 𝗘𝗥𝗠 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻
Performance management should return to its ERM roots:

• Risk identification — competence, alignment, capacity.
• Risk assessment — does the role match the person?
• Risk mitigation — training, coaching, role redesign.
• Monitoring — weekly one‑on‑ones, not annual surprises.

This is how HR becomes strategic instead of a perfomative ritual.
